metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #378
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash — they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: Neural Collapse #211
metadata.description:
What happens when your brain overloads, or when you lose control of your giant robot.

A study on the repetition and stacking of a simple but very dynamic structure.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.
You can find more informations on the piece, its design and origins, here: https://ulucode.com/wp/neural-collapse/

Interactivity : 
- You can hover your mouse on the connectors to close them... temporarily
- Press and hold the mouse button to slightly move the viewpoint.

- Press "a" to increase quality of the antialiasing (3 levels), at the cost of performances. Especially useful on the palettes using outlines.
- Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels. I recommend starting with "4".

GPU recommended. Best performances on Chrome in general.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Sugar & Splice #237
metadata.description:
'Sugar & Splice'

Vibrant somethings, full of flavor, dancing within conjoined boundaries.

Controls:
s: Saves an image of the canvas with the current settings
1-6: Scales the canvas size, from 1 (default, 2048px x 2792px) to 6 (12288px x  16752px)
g: Toggles grain texture
t: Toggles background transparency
f: Toggles fit to screen (layout and other factors will change based on the new size, but overall style, colors, etc will remain the same)
p: Shortcut for large print settings: disables the grain texture and scales the canvas to the largest setting
b: Toggles b-side 

teaboswell 2022
CC BY-NC-ND 4.0, See bundle.js.LICENSE.txt for third party license information

metadata.name: Celebration in Times of Measure #121
metadata.description:
Intentionally developed by placing constraints on the process.

Everything is generated by code written in P5js.

Press '1' for the default, textured version
Press '2' to add outlines and see the form structure

Press '3' to see a flat, untextured version
Press '4' to add outlines (flat version)

Press 'e' to end/skip the initial animation
Press 'r' to restart/replay the animation
Press 's' to save current image (in live view)

Created by Walter Anderson (@noxiarb)

metadata.name: geometric tiles #17
metadata.description:
Hello everyone, this is my first fxhash project.

There are three types of mints you can get: checkers, stairs and rectangular prisms - there is equal chance of getting any of those. 

There is also 8% chance of getting the rarity mint which is the mint with the grainy effect over it. However, you should check my twitter out in order to see the preview of all the mint types you can get.

The inspiration behind this project was M.C. Escher.

metadata.name: EccentricConcentric  #191
metadata.description:
pixelwank & Qotonana are proud to present 'EccentricConcentric' 

Exploring moire and concentric shapes, the results of EccentricConcentric are greater than the sum of its parts.

metadata.name: The Voyage #117
metadata.description:
The more we explore, the more things we realize there are to be explored. The more questions we find answers to, the more answers we find that require the right questions to be asked.

What is there beyond the edge of knowledge; what was, when things were none?

Will it be our body or our mind to discover that first?

And so The Voyage begins...

* * *

Press R to hide/show cosmic rain (takes a few seconds).
Press S to save as PNG.

Made by: yenren / twitter.com/yenrenART
Made with: JavaScript + HTML Canvas
License: LICENSE.txt

metadata.name: Sprocket Factory #428
metadata.description:
Just an ordinary scene from a typical day, working as a Sprocket Factory engineer. Inspiration for this work is drawn from the composable nature of blockchain smart contracts and the flow of value between networks of autonomous machines and free-willed individuals.

"A Doodle, Ringer, and Fidenza walk into a Space Bar..."

- Live renderer best viewed in Chrome.
- Press "P" to export an PNG raster image (10k resolution.)
- Press "S" to export an SVG vector.

metadata.name: brushstroke #25
metadata.description:
Brushstroke is an algorithm to form a minimal, modern, artistic paint on a canvas. It mimics a painter's hand gesture to apply different types of strokes. Those strokes may vary from thin straight lines to fat curvy arcs. The direction of the strokes may change for each stroke or not. There may be an excessive amount of them as there may be just several. Strokes may intersect and form a group. It generates color palettes as an artist does. There are more than twenty parameters that give variety to pieces. 

Brushstroke is built on the p5.js library. As a way of saying thanks, you will contribute to the Processing Foundation by collecting this work.

metadata.name: Takashi's Death #126
metadata.description:
Akira by Katsuhiro Otomo.
A global landmark in the shaping of the Cyberpunk genre, and a watershed title for the medium.

I got my hands on the tankōbon(s) more than 20 years ago and those pages upon pages at the end of the third one depicting the destruction of Neo-Tokyo stayed with me ever since. Pages of stunning destruction, leaving me in awe.

This is my generative take on the subject. An attempt to evoke the power of that one panel in a cohesive collection.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.
You can find more info on the composition here : https://ulucode.com/wp/takashis-death/

Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels ( height ). I recommend starting with "4".

More features are available, but a decent GPU is recommended:
- Press "space" to toggle an animation on/off
- Press "u" to Unlock the camera. You can then :
. Mouse left : Rotate
. Mouse middle/wheel : Zoom
. Mouse right : Translate
. "r" : reset camera
. "a" : change antialiasing quality : 3 settings in rotation. Try this if your framerate is too low.
